ocumentaries to anime, mass media in Japan constitute a key site in which the nation’s social memory is articulated, disseminated, and contested. Through a series of stimulating case studies, this volume examines the political and cultural representations of Japan’s past, showing how they have reinforced personal and collective narratives while also formulating new cultural meanings, both on a local scale and in the context of transnational media production and consumption. Drawing upon diverse disciplinary insights and methodologies, these studies collectively offer a nuanced account in which mass media function as much more than a simple ideological tool.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aCollective memory in mass media. 0aMass media and culturezJapan. 0aMass media and historyzJapan. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aPostwar Mass Media, Japanese Social Memory, Japanese Cinema, Social Memory, Political Discourse.1 aCenteno Martín, Marcos P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuarné, Blai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuarné, Blai, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHidaka, Katsuyuki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirsch, Griseldis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLozano-Méndez, Artur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLozano-Méndez, Artur, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMartinez, Dolores P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartinez, Dolores P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorisawa, Tomohiro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTreglia, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4